In `Controllers/FilesController.cs`, the `_logger` field is dead code — it is assigned in the constructor but never read anywhere in the class. Remove: (a) the `private readonly ILogger<FilesController> _logger;` field declaration; (b) the `ILogger<FilesController> logger` parameter from the constructor signature; (c) the `_logger = logger;` assignment; (d) the now-unused `using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;` directive at the top of the file (only if it is no longer referenced after the removal — note that `NullLogger` used by the tests is in that namespace, but the test file has its own using). Update the constructor XML doc comment to drop the logger reference. Then in `TestProject.Tests/Controllers/FilesControllerTests.cs`, update the `CreateController(FakeFileService service)` helper to construct `new FilesController(service)` (drop the second `NullLogger<FilesController>.Instance` argument) and remove the now-unused `using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;` and `using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging.Abstractions;` directives if they are no longer referenced. Do not change any other behavior. Verification: `dotnet build TestProject.sln` succeeds with no warnings about unused fields/parameters/usings; `dotnet test TestProject.Tests/TestProject.Tests.csproj` passes.

